===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|broun|lang=enm}} (the color brown from 13th century) < {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|brun|brūn|dark, shining|lang=ang}} < {{proto|Germanic|brunaz|lang=en}} < {{proto|Indo-European|bher-|shining, brown|lang=en}}. Cognates include Danish {{term|bruin|lang=da}}, Icelandic {{term|brnn|lang=is}}, Swedish {{term|brun|lang=sv}}, German {{term|braun|lang=de}}, Lithuanian {{term|brunas|lang=lt}}, {{term|beras|lang=lt}}, Sanskrit babhru {{rfscript|Devanagari|lang=sa}}, and Medieval Latin {{term|brunus|lang=la}}, Spanish {{term|bruno|lang=es}}, French {{term|brun|lang=fr}}. Confer {{term|bruin|lang=en}}, {{term|beaver|lang=en}}, {{term|burnish|lang=en}}, {{term|brunette|lang=en}}.

